userStories.notes:
The fix is in scripts/dev.ts. Two functions need updating: pipeWithPrefix (lines 43-70) and pipeTscStdout (lines 78-109).

For both functions, add a line sanitization step that:
1. Strips ANSI escape sequences commonly emitted by tsc --watch (clear screen: \x1Bc, \x1B[2J, \x1B[H, and cursor positioning sequences)
2. Trims leading whitespace

A clean approach is to define a small helper at the top of the pipe logic, e.g.:

  /** Strip ANSI clear-screen escapes and leading whitespace from a line. */
  const sanitize = (s: string): string =>
    s.replace(/\x1B(?:\[(?:[0-9;]*[A-Za-z])|c)/g, '').trimStart();

Then in both pipeWithPrefix and pipeTscStdout, apply sanitize to each line before the length check and before writing:

  for (const rawLine of lines) {
    const line = sanitize(rawLine);
    if (line.length > 0) {
      output.write(`${coloredPrefix} ${line}\n`);
    }
    // For pipeTscStdout, the sentinel check should use 'line' (sanitized)
  }

Also apply sanitize to the trailing partial line write at the end of each function.

The root cause: tsc --build --watch emits output lines with a leading space character (and sometimes ANSI clear-screen sequences). When piped through the prefix formatter, this leading space adds to the single space in the format string, producing 'prefix  content' (double space). Other processes (extension build via console.log, MCP server) don't emit leading whitespace, so they show the correct single space.

IMPORTANT: The regex for stripping ANSI sequences only needs to handle common tsc-emitted sequences. A comprehensive ANSI stripper is overkill — just handle \x1Bc (reset), \x1B[2J (clear), \x1B[H (cursor home), and general CSI sequences \x1B[...letter. Leave color sequences alone — tsc in watch mode with piped output typically doesn't emit colors, and our prefix already adds/resets colors.

Actually, on reflection, it's simpler and safer to strip ALL ANSI escape sequences from child process output, since we're adding our own color prefixes. Use a broader regex:

  const ANSI_RE = /[\x1B\x9B](?:\[[0-9;]*[A-Za-z]|\].*?(?:\x07|\x1B\\)|[()#][AB012]|c)/g;
  const sanitize = (s: string): string => s.replace(ANSI_RE, '').trimStart();

This prevents any ANSI garbage from child processes from corrupting the prefixed output.
